application   choupoProps;
description   "Ion-exchange SOFTENING of a brackish RO feed removes the scaling driver. Three acts on the same water as scaling_ro_brackish: (1) raw -- a scalingScan shows calcite SI > 0 already at the feed and climbing with recovery (the CaCO3-supersaturation problem). (2) softened -- the `exchange` op equilibrates the water with a strong-acid cation resin (SAC_Na, Gaines-Thomas mass action): the SAME log-space Newton as speciate PLUS one master (the free resin site X-), one balance (CEC capacity), and the half-reactions Me + zX = MeX; divalent Ca2+ (logK 0.8) is equivalent-fraction-favoured and outcompetes Na+, so Ca and Mg drop ~99% onto the resin while Na rises eq-for-eq (the salt penalty, in meq/L); hardness_removal_pct ~ 99%. (3) softened_scaling -- feed the softened composition into a scalingScan and SI_calcite is now NEGATIVE across the whole recovery range: the scaling DRIVER is gone. THE CAVEAT (printed, non-suppressible): exchange returns the LIMITING fully-equilibrated effluent (a fresh/fully-loaded contactor), NOT a bed in service -- a real bed leaks rising hardness to breakthrough then needs regeneration (transient, not modelled). Cross-check: PHREEQC EXCHANGE. Brackish I ~ 0.03-0.06: Davies-valid.";
verbosity     3;
